## Purpose  
I want to see how well multiplayer games do on steam compared to the average game, as well as trying to identify any trends, outliers, and undermarketed regions of the genre.

While the db I'm using does supply an owner count range, it's both imprecise and you can’t reliably say owners purchased the game (i.e. free game weekends where people who temporarily own a game are counted), so instead I’m using review count. Estimated ratios seen below

![][image1]  
Source: https://howtomarketagame.com/benchmarks/

Some games on steam have adult content tags, I plan to filter out all games with such tags since this is a school project.

Because the database is from late 2024, there are chances that there’s trends I would only see from an up-to-date database, or that some trends are outdated. I could scrape my own data but this seems out of scope for the project, so I'm settling for this.

On the technical side, I’m using an SQL Database, and I want to try to use some SQL features that R wouldn’t be able to handle as well. R has libraries for SQL for this.

## Question overview

1. Genre, Tags  
2. Review count, Review count among multiplayer games  
   1. I’d also like to find a random sample of games for each quartile so I can individually see what they do wrong and right. Humans are more complex than pure numbers so seeing actual pages will help.  
3. Tags and review category among multiplayer games  
4. Publishers and review count among multiplayer games  
5. Price and review count among multiplayer games

## Code architecture overview

`r_scripts/` stores all the R scripts, each subfolder is for each section at https://docs.google.com/document/d/1xnqAVPpmZMMaGAcvEOveP_4wgJM0G5lv2u3Dfd2XBwo/edit?tab=t.0, with each R script being for each question (skipped questions wouldn't be valid for the format, i.e. overlapping categories)

`r_scripts/base.r` contains the setup for each R script, aswell as some convenience variables

`config.r` contains some general settings, but has grown mostly unused
